              inference and traditional approaches to mediation analysis and
              making a case for the need for explicit causal thinking and the
              causal inference approach in mediation analysis. It then explains
              in as-plain-as-possible language existing effect types, paying
              special attention to motivating these effects with different
              types of research questions, and using concrete examples for
              illustration. This presentation differentiates 2 perspectives (or
              purposes of analysis): the explanatory perspective (aiming to
              explain the total effect) and the interventional perspective
              (asking questions about hypothetical interventions on the
              exposure and mediator, or hypothetically modified exposures). For
              the latter perspective, the article proposes tapping into a
              general class of interventional effects that contains as special
